Nature of the Result This chapter performs a boundary value inversion: it determines the unique value of the Higgs quartic coupling λ(Q₀) that reproduces the observed Higgs mass at low energy under the adopted RGE system. The result
λ(Q_0)≈-0.095
is not interpreted as a prediction of λ from geometry, but as the boundary coordinate required for consistency with the Standard Model scalar mass.


Falsification Gate This capsule is falsified if any of the following occur:
	A different λ(Q₀) reproduces the Higgs mass under the same RGE system.
	The downward evolution becomes unstable or non perturbative.
	Updated PDG inputs shift λ(Q₀) outside the corridor compatible with the gauge sector boundary values.
	A higher loop or threshold corrected RGE system produces a λ(Q₀) inconsistent with the value used in Chapter 5.5b.
This keeps the scalar sector tied to the same constraint architecture as the gauge sectors.


Relation to the Gauge Corridor The scalar boundary coordinate λ(Q₀) interacts with the gauge boundary values through the coupled RGE system. The magnitude and sign of λ(Q₀) influence the hypercharge trajectory and are therefore essential for the corrected electromagnetic capsule (5.5b). This chapter does not claim that λ(Q₀) is determined by the gauge corridor, but it establishes that the scalar coordinate must be compatible with the gauge boundary values for the full system to remain perturbative and consistent.






